   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                              target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref></title></hi>].
                        <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"><title><title><ref
                                    target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref></title>; A
                              Tragedy, In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                                 >William Shakspeare</ref>. As Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>, London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. IV. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King
                        Lear</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title></hi>. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#Macbeth"
                                 >Macbeth</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref></title></hi>.
                           <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#AntoniusMarcus"
                                 >Antony</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CleopatraVIIQueenofEgypt"
                              >Cleopatra</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst,
                        Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play
                        was staged at the Globe Theatre on September 21<hi rendition="#sup">st</hi>,
                        1599. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi
                           rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>It rarely happens, that a theatre is enriched by a number of male performers, equal
               to the task of representing those great historical characters, which <ref
                  target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> has here pourtrayed with
               his usual truth of delineation.</p>

            <p>The theatres of London, at the present era, can boast of actors to set all such
               difficulties at defiance; and yet it has been thought adviseable, for some years
               past, that this tragedy should not appear upon the stage.</p>

            <p>When men's thoughts are deeply engaged on public events, historical occurrences, of a
               similar kind, are only held proper for the contemplation of such minds as know how to
               distinguish, and to appreciate, the good and the evil with which they abound. Such
               discriminating judges do not compose the whole audience of a playhouse; therefore,
               when the circumstances of certain periods make certain incidents of history most
               interesting, those are the very seasons to interdict their exhibition.</p>

            <p>Till the time of the world's repose, then, the lovers of the drama will, probably, be
               compelled to accept of real conspiracies, assassinations, and the slaughter of war,
               in lieu of such spectacles, ably counterfeited.</p>
            <fw type="sig">
               <hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi>
            </fw>
            <pb n="4"/>

            <p><ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr. Johnson</ref> has said of this
               play&#8212;"I have never been strongly agitated in perusing it, and think it somewhat
               cold and unaffecting, compared with some other of <ref
                  target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>'s plays: his adherence to
               the true story, and to Roman manners, seem to have impeded the natural vigour of his
                  genius."<note>From <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays of <ref
                           target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakespeare</ref>, With
                        the Corrections and Illustrations of Various Commentators</title></hi>
                  (1765), vol. 7, p. 102.</note></p>

            <p>Had <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> lived in the present time,
               perhaps this very "adherence to the true story," would have excited that warmth, and
               that interest, of the absence of which he complains. A relish for the food of the
               mind is to be created by a certain stimulus, the same as an appetite for the
               nourishment of the body; and, in these days, political wonders occur to inspire a
               more than common concern about all those that are past. </p>

            <p>In this admirable drama is a short, and yet exact, narration, of the most remarkable
               crisis in the Roman history. Every character is described by a faithful
               pen&#8212;every virtuous and every wicked design nicely explained, by a penetrating
               and an impartial commentator upon the heart of man.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#Voltaire">Voltaire</ref>'s tragedy,<note><ref
                     target="people.html#Voltaire">Voltaire</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Death of <ref target="people.html#CaesarJulius"
                        >Caesar</ref></title></hi> (<hi rendition="#italics"><title>Mort de <ref
                           target="people.html#CaesarJulius">C&#233;sar</ref></title></hi>)
                  (1735).</note> on the same subject, has a degree of peculiar interest, on account
               of his representing, though from doubtful authority, the close relationship, which
               subsisted between <ref target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Cæsar</ref> and <ref
                  target="people.html#BrutusMarcus">Brutus</ref>, as father and son; but the
               sympathy awakened by truth, and nothing but known truth, is surely more forcible with
               the generality of readers, than that which arises from a source, the least tending
               towards fiction.</p>

            <p>Some critics have objected to <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref>'s conti-<pb n="5"/>nuation of the play after the death of <ref
                  target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Cæsar</ref>; supposing that great event would
               have been more powerful than any other for the catastrophe: but it is hardly possible
               to read to the end, and wish any thing altered; unless, perhaps, that <ref
                  target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Cæsar</ref>'s character had been rendered more
               prominent in those few scenes where he is introduced. This drama is not, however,
               designed to represent the life, but solely the death, of <ref
                  target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref>. The poet has not attempted
               to show in action, even by one important incident, how this conqueror of the world
               lived,&#8212;but merely how he died.</p>

            <p>In so short a composition as a play some characters must necessarily be compressed;
               and, in the original editions of this work, <ref target="people.html#Cicero"
                  >Cicero</ref>'s has been more than any other diminished. That celebrated orator is
               there placed amongst the dramatis personæ, and has scarcely been given a word to
               say.</p>

            <p>The following account from <ref target="people.html#UptonJohn">Upton</ref> will be of
               use to the reader: <quote>The real length of time in '<title><ref
                        target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref></title>' is as follows:
                  About the middle of February, A.U.C. 709, a frantic festival, sacred to <ref
                     target="people.html#Pan">Pan</ref>,<note>The pastoral festival Lupercalia was
                     celebrated by Ancient Romans on February 15<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> with
                     the aim of purifying the city to promote fertility and wellbeing.</note> was
                  held in honour of <ref target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Cæsar</ref>, when the
                  royal crown was offered him by <ref target="people.html#AntoniusMarcus">Marc
                     Antony</ref>. On the 15th of March, in the same year, he was slain. A.U.C. 711,
                     <ref target="people.html#BrutusMarcus">Brutus</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#Cassius">Cassius</ref> were defeated near
                     Philippi.<note>From <ref target="people.html#UptonJohn">John Upton</ref>'s <hi
                        rendition="#italics"><title>Critical Observations on <ref
                              target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref></title></hi>
                     (1746), p. 74.</note></quote></p>
            <fw type="sig">
               <hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi>
            </fw>
         </div>
      </body>
